{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.12,0.02,0.14,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11285"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61177"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"10805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26173"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with a painless ulcer on her genitals that appeared three weeks ago. Despite the visible tissue damage, there is notably minimal surrounding inflammation or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes why some infections produce minimal host inflammatory response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pathogen evades immune recognition mechanisms","Infection occurs in immunologically privileged sites","Host immune system is completely suppressed","Pathogen replicates at extremely slow rates","Pathogen produces toxins that destroy immune cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Epathogen evades immune recognition mechanisms\u003C/strong\u003E. Some microorganisms have evolved sophisticated strategies to avoid detection by the immune system, resulting in minimal inflammation despite ongoing infection. This is particularly seen in infections like syphilis, tuberculosis, and leprosy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPathogen produces toxins that destroy immune cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This would typically result in significant inflammation and tissue damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHost immune system is completely suppressed\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete immune suppression would lead to multiple opportunistic infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfection occurs in immunologically privileged sites\u003C/strong\u003E - These sites still mount immune responses when infected\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPathogen replicates at extremely slow rates\u003C/strong\u003E - While some minimal response pathogens do replicate slowly, this alone does not explain the lack of immune response\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinimal host response infections are characterized by limited inflammation despite significant pathogen presence. This occurs through various mechanisms including molecular mimicry, antigenic variation, and intracellular survival strategies that help pathogens avoid immune detection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Minimal host response infections occur when pathogens evade or suppress immune recognition.","Common examples of minimal host response infections include tuberculosis, leprosy, and syphilis.","Minimal host response infections typically present with minimal inflammation despite significant tissue damage."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61177"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61177"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T13:16:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T13:17:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11285"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https:/